Due to the extreme popularity of the beautiful white  
tigers among zoo guests, and because these animals  
tolerate captivity very well, they have been part of an  
aggressive breeding program. Some conservationists  
find this disturbing, since some subspecies of tigers  
hover on the verge of extinction, and the white tiger  
is considered an aberrant Bengal tiger, rather than a  
valid subspecies.  
 
Since white tigers have been bred indiscriminately  
with the other subspecies of tigers, particularly the  
Siberian, it is assumed that most of the white tigers  
in captivity today are hybrids. 
 
